John,<br><br>
This is a beautiful account of the incident.  I was out of country and didn't return until the first of May 1972.  Just missed the SAR effort, but not the action around Quang Tri.<br><br>
I believe the Nail FACs were very active.  A friend of mine during this time frame was self-teaching himself to land an OV10 on a carrier to take on fuel to minimize time off station.  Nobody would give up.<br><br>
I know why they were intense about the efforts.  A lot of the guys from the EB66s was either from Strat Recon, intell, or strategic nuclear.  All very desirable POWs.  On some of our missions, depending on the mix of guys, we weren't allowed to over fly certain areas for the same reasons.  There were those who decided that capture would not be an option, my self included.  In hostile areas they disconnected their chute .A very good friend of mine who I work with today was an Eb66 pilot during this time frame (Strat Recon).  On many a night I have waited outside of Haiphong to escort the whale home.  The navy called it the A-3 Whale.<br><br>
The willingness of so many to lay down their lives for so few was something I saw repeatedly.  I wished others could have the privilege to serve with such men.<br><br>
John, out the list of causalities I think I see the name of an old fly buddy.  Thanks I'll check my records to confirm.<br><br>
Stories such as this need to be told.  I hope the families find the same comfort, as have I in your needing to tell the rest of the story.<br><br>
God Bless<br>

